    body: "Photos used to be reliable proof that something happened. If you saw a photo of a person standing in front of a famous building, you could trust they were really there. In 2026, that is no longer true. Free websites can now create lifelike photos of any person, place, or event in seconds, based only on a written description. These are called AI-generated photos, or synthetic images. They show up in news articles, on Facebook, in scam emails asking for charity donations, and in fake stories meant to make people angry or afraid. Federal Bureau of Investigation reports indicate AI image fraud cost Americans over $2 billion in 2025, with the largest growth coming from romance scams and charity fraud aimed at seniors.\n\nThe most common ways seniors run into AI-generated photos are these: a fake romance interest sends pictures that look like a model but turn out to be made up; a charity scam after a hurricane shows children in rubble who never existed; a political post shares an outrageous photo of a politician that turns out to be fabricated; an obituary scam uses an AI photo to make a fake death announcement look real, then asks for funeral donations. The technology has improved so fast that even careful viewers can be fooled. But fake photos still have a handful of giveaway flaws that you can learn to spot in under a minute.\n\nThe good news is that you do not need special software or technical training to catch most AI photos. The same eyes that helped you sort real things from fake your whole life still work, you only need to know what to look for. AI photo software is very good at making big shapes look right, like faces, bodies, and backgrounds. It is much worse at small details, especially hands, ears, jewelry, eyes, and written text. Looking at those small details is the fastest way to tell a real photo from a fake one. This guide shows the seven checks that work most of the time, in the order you should do them.\n\nBefore you begin, find a photo you want to check. It might be one from a news article, an email, a Facebook post, or a dating app profile. Have it open on your screen large enough that you can see the small details. If the photo is too small, click or tap it to make it bigger. Have a notepad handy. None of these checks require any download or any special tool, only your eyes and a careful look. The whole process for one photo takes about two minutes once you have practiced it a few times.",
